<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06180214 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06180214 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  EUROPE; GOVERNMENT; OFFICIAL; YUGOSLAVIA; END; ETHNIC; STATE; WAR  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  European Community leaders sent officials to Yugoslavia today to try toarrange talks between the Belgrade government and two breakaway republics. Italso said it would freeze aid to the strife-torn federation.;    &quot;Europe muststop the evolution toward civil war in Yugoslavia,&quot; said Italian PremierGiulio Andreotti.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  EC SEEKS TO BRING FACTIONS TOGETHER  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The EC delegation left this afternoon shortly before Yugoslavia's federalarmy declared a cease-fire and said its troops had captured all border postsin the breakaway republic of Slovenia. Slovenia and the neighboring republicof Croatia declared independence Tuesday.;    A British official who spoke oncondition of anonymity said the delegation would seek a three-month truce.Under the plan, Slovenia and Croatia would suspend their declarations ofindependence and all troops would return to their barracks, the officialsaid.;    The foreign ministers of Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands weresent to Belgrade after the 12-nation trade bloc decided to put on holdeconomic assistance to Yugoslavia.;    The decision came at the start of atwo-day summit called to discuss political and economic union for the EC,topics initially overshadowed by the Yugoslav crisis.;    &quot;It is a highlydangerous situation,&quot; Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd of Britain said. &quot;We needto find ways to help cool things down.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Luxembourg  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910628  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  22A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  2